<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1217" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1217">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 367.116/228</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi> to <persName type="to">
                                <hi rend="italic">G. T. W. Patrick</hi>
                            </persName>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-09">
                                <hi rend="italic">November 9, 1914</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Your November 6.<note n="1" xml:id="d1217fn1">Not printed.</note>
                            Personal telegram to James L. Barton, of Boston, dated November 7 and
                            transmitted by American Ambassador at Constantinople reads as
                            follows:</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>American Ambassador with hearty cooperation of Turkish officials has
                                situation completely in hand. Missionaries and their work fully
                                safeguarded. Everything proceeding as though normal conditions
                                prevailed. You may safely reassure all friends.</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_PWW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Peet</hi>
                                </persName>
                                <lb/>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>